[
  {
    "op": "MODIFY",
    "section": "action_execution",
    "target_id": "acti-005",
    "content": "acti-005: IF calling modify_pending_order_items, modify_pending_order_address, exchange_delivered_order_items, return_delivered_order_items, cancel_pending_order, or any other tooling call that modifies an order's state → THEN verify every item_id listed to be replaced, exchanged, or returned is present in the most recently retrieved order details for that order_id. If any provided item_id is not found in the current cached order state, call get_order_details(order_id) to refresh and reconcile the order contents, inform the user of the mismatch, and ask the user to confirm the correct item_ids (or which order they intended) before making the tooling call. Do not execute any tooling call with invalid or out-of-order item_ids.\n\nAlso verify the order's current status is appropriate for the requested tooling call (for modify_pending_order_items and modify_pending_order_address the order must be 'pending'; for exchange_delivered_order_items and return_delivered_order_items the order must be 'delivered'). IF you do not have up-to-date order details or the cached state may be stale, call get_order_details(order_id) to refresh the order state before proceeding. For actions that propose replacement item_ids (e.g., modify_pending_order_items or exchanges), verify each proposed new_item_id exists, is available, and is different from the current item_id (for example by calling get_product_details(product_id) or otherwise validating variant availability and item_id existence). Verify that counts and any replacement rules required by the tooling are satisfied (for example, equal counts when required). If any new_item_id is unavailable, identical to the current item, or would violate tooling count constraints, inform the user, present alternatives, and obtain explicit confirmation of the exact replacements before calling the tooling. Do not call modify_pending_order_items, modify_pending_order_address, exchange_delivered_order_items, or return_delivered_order_items if the order state does not match the action required.\n\nAfter successfully performing any tooling call that modifies an order's state, immediately call get_order_details(order_id) to refresh the order state before attempting any further actions on that same order in the session. Present the refreshed order summary to the user (including updated items, item_ids, order status, and payment_history) and explicitly confirm with the user that they want to proceed with any additional changes. Before attempting any further modifications that change payment_method_id or payment allocation for that order, retrieve and present the user's available on-file payment methods (including type and identifiable label such as last four) and obtain explicit confirmation of which payment method to use (see acti-015). If get_order_details reveals the order is no longer in a modifiable state, inform the user immediately, explain the limitation, and offer alternatives (for example: place a new order, escalate to a human agent, or accept the current state). Do not retry modification tooling calls without a refreshed order state and explicit user confirmation of any changed parameters (including payment method).",
    "rationale": "Agents attempted further changes (including switching payment methods) without refreshing the order state and without presenting available payment methods; a stronger requirement to refresh and present the updated order and to obtain explicit confirmation (especially for payment changes) will prevent failed retries like in Conversation 5.",
    "source_task_ids": [
      5
    ]
  },
  {
    "op": "ADD",
    "section": "action_execution",
    "target_id": null,
    "content": "acti-023: IF modify_pending_order_items cannot remove a specific item (for example because replacements must be 1:1 or 'Variant not found') and the user requests removal of one or more items from a pending order → THEN: (a) explain clearly that modify_pending_order_items cannot remove items without a same-count replacement and list the supported alternatives (cancel the entire order, leave the order as-is, or place a separate new order for the desired items); (b) if the user indicates they prefer cancelling the entire order as the chosen alternative, explicitly confirm with the user that cancelling will cancel every item in the order and trigger a full-order refund per system policy (state the refund destination and any relevant timing expectations); (c) offer to place a new order for the remaining/desired items on the user's behalf or guide the user through placing a new order if they prefer to preserve some items; (d) obtain an explicit, unambiguous confirmation from the user that they want the entire order cancelled (not just the single item) before calling cancel_pending_order(order_id, reason). If the user does not provide explicit confirmation of whole-order cancellation, do not call cancel_pending_order; instead proceed with the selected alternative (new order, keep existing order, or escalate).",
    "rationale": "An agent canceled an entire pending order after a failed item-level replacement despite the user asking to remove a single item and add a different one; the playbook must require an explicit confirmation that the user understands cancel_pending_order will cancel the whole order and offer the option to place a new order for replacements to avoid unintended full-order cancellations (observed in Conversation 4).",
    "source_task_ids": [
      4
    ]
  }
]

[
  {
    "op": "MODIFY",
    "section": "action_execution",
    "target_id": "acti-001",
    "content": "IF the order status is 'pending' and the user requests to change/replace a pending item → THEN call modify_pending_order_items(order_id, item_ids, new_item_ids, payment_method_id). ADDITIONAL REQUIREMENT: If the proposed replacements would result in any price difference (the new items cost more or less than the items being replaced), do NOT call modify_pending_order_items until you have: (a) computed the price difference (by comparing current order item prices and the new variant prices, using get_product_details or other tooling as needed), (b) presented the exact price difference to the user (showing whether it is an additional charge or a refund, the amount, and how it will be applied), (c) retrieved and presented the user's available on-file payment methods (including type and identifiable label such as last four) if the user has not already specified a payment_method_id and indicated which methods the tooling supports for the requested action, and (d) obtained the user's explicit confirmation of the exact payment method to use and explicit agreement to proceed with the computed charge/refund. If the original payment was a gift card, follow prec-001 and acti-013 regarding refund destinations and make this clear to the user before proceeding. Only after the user confirms the payment method and the price-difference handling should you call modify_pending_order_items. If the user does not confirm, offer alternatives (place a new order, cancel the pending order, or adjust the requested replacements).",
    "rationale": "Trajectories showed modify_pending_order_items being executed and an extra charge applied (Conversation 2) without the assistant presenting payment methods and obtaining explicit confirmation of the payment method and price difference beforehand. The playbook previously required payment confirmation in some contexts but did not explicitly mandate it prior to calling modify_pending_order_items when a price difference exists.",
    "source_task_ids": [
      2,
      5
    ]
  },
  {
    "op": "MODIFY",
    "section": "action_execution",
    "target_id": "acti-015",
    "content": "IF the user requests that refunds/price differences be applied to 'another on-file payment method' but does not specify which one → THEN first retrieve and present the user's available on-file payment methods (prefer non-gift-card methods when the original payment was not a gift card) including identifiable labels (type and last four digits or other label) and indicate which methods the tooling supports for the requested action. Additionally, when a requested action will create a price difference (either a charge or a refund), explicitly show the calculated price difference amount and clearly state whether the user will be charged or refunded, and which on-file payment method (type and last four or other identifiable label) will be used for that charge or refund. Prompt the user to explicitly select and confirm which on-file payment method to use and obtain explicit confirmation of the exact amount and payment method before proceeding. Only after the user confirms a specific payment method and the exact price difference, proceed with the order-changing action using that payment_method_id. If the original payment was a gift card, prefer non‑gift-card methods only when supported by tooling and policy; if tooling does not support changing the refund/payment destination from the original gift card, inform the user and obtain explicit confirmation to proceed with the system behavior. IF no suitable alternate payment method is available, inform the user and offer alternatives (for example: add a new payment method, use a different on-file method they confirm, initiate a return flow if appropriate, or escalate to a human agent). BEFORE executing any irreversible order-changing action, inform the user which on-file payment method (type and last four digits or other identifiable label) will be used and obtain explicit confirmation. IF the user does not confirm, prompt the user to specify which payment method to use or fall back to refunding to the original payment method per policy.",
    "rationale": "Evidence (Conversation 2) showed a pending-order modification that resulted in an additional charge being applied without the assistant explicitly presenting the calculated price difference and obtaining confirmation of the payment method beforehand. Strengthening acti-015 to require presentation of the exact amount (charge or refund) and explicit confirmation closes this gap.",
    "source_task_ids": [
      2
    ]
  }
]

