  {
    "op": "MODIFY",
    "section": "action_execution",
    "target_id": "acti-002",
    "content": "IF the order status is 'delivered' and the user requests to either exchange or return delivered items → THEN for an exchange call exchange_delivered_order_items(order_id, item_ids, new_item_ids, payment_method_id); for a return call return_delivered_order_items(order_id, item_ids, payment_method_id). ADDITIONAL REQUIREMENT: If the proposed exchange will result in any price difference (the new items cost more or less than the items being exchanged), do NOT call exchange_delivered_order_items until you have: (a) computed the exact price difference (using get_product_details or other tooling as needed), (b) presented the exact price difference to the user (showing whether it is an additional charge or a refund, the amount, and how it will be applied), (c) retrieved and presented the user's available on-file payment methods (including type and identifiable label such as last four) if the user has not already specified a payment_method_id and indicated which methods the tooling supports for the requested action, and (d) obtained the user's explicit confirmation of the exact payment method to use and explicit agreement to proceed with the computed charge/refund. If the user does not confirm, offer alternatives (initiate a return, choose a different replacement, or escalate to a human agent). After performing an exchange_delivered_order_items call that modifies payment allocation or records an exchange_price_difference, follow acti-005: verify items and order state, and refresh order details (call get_order_details(order_id)) unless the tooling response includes full, authoritative order details.",
    "rationale": "Delivered-item exchanges in the trajectories were executed without first presenting and confirming payment-method selection and the exact price difference. The playbook already requires this for pending-order modifications, so require the same explicit price-difference and payment-method confirmation for delivered exchanges to avoid unexpected charges/refunds.",
    "source_task_ids": [1,4]
  }
]

[
  {
    "op": "MODIFY",
    "section": "action_execution",
    "target_id": "acti-005",
    "content": "acti-005 (updated): IF calling modify_pending_order_items, modify_pending_order_address, exchange_delivered_order_items, return_delivered_order_items, cancel_pending_order, or any other tooling call that modifies an order's state → THEN verify every item_id listed to be replaced, exchanged, or returned is present in the most recently retrieved order details for that order_id. If any provided item_id is not found in the current cached order state, call get_order_details(order_id) to refresh and reconcile the order contents, inform the user of the mismatch, and ask the user to confirm the correct item_ids (or which order they intended) before making the tooling call. Do not execute any tooling call with invalid or out-of-order item_ids.\n\nAlso verify the order's current status is appropriate for the requested tooling call (for modify_pending_order_items and modify_pending_order_address the order must be 'pending'; for exchange_delivered_order_items and return_delivered_order_items the order must be 'delivered'). IF the order is already in an active return/exchange state (for example 'return requested' or 'exchange requested'), do NOT assume you can append additional items by re-calling return_delivered_order_items or exchange_delivered_order_items. Instead: (a) call get_order_details(order_id) to confirm the current return/exchange activity and which item_ids are already included, (b) check whether the tooling explicitly supports adding items to an existing return/exchange request before attempting the call, and (c) if the tooling does NOT support modifying an existing return/exchange, inform the user that additional items cannot be appended to the current request and present alternatives (initiate a separate return/exchange for the additional items, cancel and re-create the return/exchange if appropriate, or escalate to a human agent to request a manual merge/adjustment). Obtain explicit user confirmation of which alternative to proceed with before taking any further action. Do not repeatedly retry adding items without tooling confirmation or explicit user confirmation of the chosen alternative.\n\nWhen a user requests exchanging or modifying multiple quantities of the same product, explicitly verify that the order contains that many distinct item_ids (each unit must be represented by an actual item_id in the order). Do NOT assume that repeating a single item_id multiple times is valid. If the requested quantity exceeds the number of matching item_ids in the referenced order, or if the user references multiple units that may span multiple orders, ask the user to (a) specify the exact item_id(s) and/or order_id(s) to act on, or (b) confirm you should search their recent orders for matching item_ids. If items span multiple orders, do not combine item_ids from different orders into a single tooling call; instead follow the multi-order exchange handling rules (perform per-order verification and per-order tooling calls).\n\nIf any new_item_id is unavailable, identical to the current item, or would violate tooling count constraints, inform the user, present alternatives, and obtain explicit confirmation of the exact replacements before calling the tooling. Do not call modify_pending_order_items, modify_pending_order_address, exchange_delivered_order_items, or return_delivered_order_items if the order state does not match the action required.\n\nAfter successfully performing any tooling call that modifies an order's state, immediately call get_order_details(order_id) to refresh the order state BEFORE attempting any further actions on that same order in the session and present the refreshed order summary to the user (including updated items, item_ids, order status, and payment_history). EXCEPTION: If the modifying tooling call's response itself includes the full, authoritative, up-to-date order details (items, item_ids, order status, and payment_history) returned by the system, a separate immediate get_order_details(order_id) call is optional. In that case, the assistant must verify the tooling response includes complete order details and may use that response to present the refreshed order summary. If the tooling response does not include full order details or its completeness is uncertain, the assistant MUST call get_order_details(order_id) to refresh state before further actions. Before attempting any further modifications that change payment_method_id or payment allocation for that order, retrieve and present the user's available on-file payment methods (including type and identifiable label such as last four) and obtain explicit confirmation of which payment method to use (see acti-015). If get_order_details reveals the order is no longer in a modifiable state, inform the user immediately, explain the limitation, and offer alternatives (for example: place a new order, escalate to a human agent, or accept the current state). Do not retry modification tooling calls without a refreshed order state and explicit user confirmation of any changed parameters (including payment method).",
    "rationale": "Trajectories showed an attempt to add items to an order already marked 'return requested' which failed; the playbook lacked explicit instructions to check whether tooling supports appending items to existing return/exchange requests and to present alternatives when not supported.",
    "source_task_ids": [
      "Conversation 1"
    ]
  },
  {
